Controlling Drugs in the United States: An Endless War?
Enis Aldemir July 2011, TX

Controlling Drugs in the United States: An Endless War? 1. Introduction
Drug abuse is one of the most important policy issues in the United States for more than a century. Federal, state, and local policy makers tend to solve this problem by means of deterrence, treatment, and educational programs, and by increasing punishments for the users and sellers, however the issue is still remains on top of the agenda. Since enactment of San Francisco ordinance in 1875, U.S. policy makers have continued to adopt law after law, attempting to deal with this problem.
Although law enforcement and prevention measures took the first place in the struggle against drug abuse in the early efforts, this approach changed dramatically in due course. Furthermore, in line with the advancement of neurobiological studies, the disease model of addiction became widely accepted and rather than punitive measures, educational programs and treatment options were mostly favored.
This paper aims to draw an outline of the control measures and sanctions imposed for the usage, sale, and possession of illegal drugs and controlled substances in the U.S. The second part of the paper focuses on early efforts of prevention, including temperance movement, prohibition, and other measures. The third part discusses the developments after the Controlled Substances Act of 1970 and modern approaches to the drug abuse problem.
2. Early Efforts of Prevention 2.1. Alcoholism and Temperance Movement Although getting drunk has the same bad reputation among various cultures, beverage
alcohol has developed different footprints. In line with the religious tenets, some cultures
1

consider usage of alcohol -except medical purposes- as a sin; on the other hand, some other cultures use alcohol, especially the wine as a part of their religious rituals. People’s likelihood of being addicted to alcohol is directly related with cultural views and appreciation of it. In this regard existing literature on alcoholism share that, the U.S. and other Protestant Englishspeaking nations have traditionally consumed large quantities of alcohol, which leaded both high rates of social and health problems, including alcohol related mortality (Peele 2010, Abadinsky 2011). Starting with the initiatives of Dr. Benjamin Rush in late 1700s, alcohol was believed to be an important cause of moral degeneration, poverty and crime among the nation. The arguments flamed in the 1800s with the active participation of Protestant churches, which leaded establishment of temperance unions that will be the main facilitators of a nationwide prohibition in 1919 (Abadinsky 2011).
The temperance view of abstinence had different views on the modern alcoholism: Firstly, although these two movements see alcoholism as a problem, their identifications of the problem are totally different. The temperance ideology saw alcohol inherently evil and inevitably dangerous for everyone (Peele 1995, 2010; Tracy 2007). However, modern alcoholism movement considers it as a disease that should be cured. Secondly, policy alternatives that these ideologies offer to the problem are fundamentally different. Today, modern alcoholism movement preaches moderation, whereas the temperance view in the nineteenth century supported the abstinence to be forced through prohibition (Abadinsky 2011).
2.2. National Prohibition The National Prohibition Act was the legislation that enabled eighteenth amendment, which outlawed the sale of alcoholic beverages that have an alcohol content of greater than 0.5 percent between 1920 and 1933. With the pressures of the temperance movement, the eighteenth
2

amendment of the constitution was ratified in 36 states until 1919 and the congress passed the National Prohibition Act in 1920, which is usually referred to as Volstead Act after its sponsor, Minnesota Congressman Andrew Volstead, over President Woodrow Wilson’s veto. The law enabled the legal definition of intoxicating liquor, as well as penalties for producing it and provided for federal enforcement (Abadinsky 2011).
Mennell (1969) argues that the movement to legislate against alcohol had deep roots. Ratification of eighteenth amendment in many northern and mid-western states was a result of the growing social consciousness of the churches in the 1840s and a850s. Abadinsky (2011) points out the contention and claims that, national prohibition was a measure passed by village America against urban America, as well as by Protestant America against Catholic America. Although the movement weakened in the time of Civil War and most of the existing legislation was repealed, fast growth of the liquor trade between 1860 and 1880 caused a number of social problems including drunkenness and loss of labor productivity. Furthermore, liquor interests frequently allied themselves to corrupt politicians and vice rings, the saloon became a center of prostitution, crime, and political graft (Mennell 1969). According to Thornton (1991), the "noble experiment" (national prohibition of alcohol) initially aimed to reduce crime and corruption, solve social problems, reduce the tax burden created by prisons and poorhouses, and improve health and hygiene in America. The National Prohibition Act is basically flourished from those sentiments among the conservatives and with the aim of solving social and criminal problems. However, scholars agree that the results of the noble experiment were failure on most of the accounts (Thornton 1991; Mennell 1969). Schrad (2010) defines the prohibition of alcohol as a mistake, a historic policy gaffe, a political fiasco and a bad idea when compared with the more effective policy alternatives. Furthermore, it eroded respect for law, eliminated a valuable stream
3

of government revenue as well as caused corruption, bootlegging and inflation in crime rates (Abadinsky 2011; Schrad 2010). As a result of these negative consequences, the Congress repealed the eighteenth amendment in 1933 and restored control of alcohol to the states.
2.3. Opium Control and Chinese Immigrants The economic depression in 1875 resulted the first significant piece of prohibitive drug legislation enacted by the City of San Francisco. The primary reason that precipitated the campaign against the Chinese and against opium was the sudden onset of economic depression, high unemployment levels, and the disintegration of working-class standards of living. The San Francisco ordinance prohibited the operation of opium dens, commercial establishments for the smoking of opium, not because of health concerns as such, but because it was believed that the drug stimulated coolies into working harder than non-smoking whites. The regulation targeted opium smoking, but not other methods of ingestion. As a result of this discrepancy, some scholars believe that these early laws were possibly racist in origin and intent (Abadinsky 2011). 2.4. Twentieth Century Efforts and Legislation Abadinsky (2011) argues that, national efforts against opium and cocaine were part of a larger campaign to regulate drugs and the contents of food substances. The regulation efforts of the Congress continued with the Pure Food and Drug Act of 1906, which imposed regulations on the labeling of products containing alcohol, morphine, opium, cocaine, heroin, alpha or beta eucaine, chloroform, cannabis indica, chloral hydrate, or acetanilide. It required that products containing any of those substances be labeled with the substance and quantity on the label. This was followed by the Harrison Act, passed in 1914, which regulated drugs by imposing licensing requirements on manufacturers, distributors, sellers, importers, producers, compounders, and dispensers. The Harrison Act required these parties to register with the
4

director of Internal Revenue, within the Treasury Department, and to pay a gradually increasing occupational tax. Congress wanted to monitor the flow of opium and coca leaves so that government would have records of any transaction involving these drugs. They would be allowed only for limited medical and scientific purposes. Those individuals who violate the act faced a maximum penalty of five years in jail, a $2,000 fine, or both (Carson-DeWitt 2001).
Anti drug efforts remained mostly federal until 1930, only a few states had drug control statutes, and these were generally ineffective. At the urging of federal authorities, many states enacted their own antidrug legislation. By 1931 every state banned the sale of cocaine, and all but two restricted the sale of opiates. State statutes, however, were far from uniform. As early as 1927, this lack of uniformity, combined with the growing hysteria about dope fiends and criminality, resulted in several requests for a uniform state narcotics law. The diversity of state drug statutes was not an anachronism. The need for greater uniformity in state statutes was recognized in the first half of the nineteenth century, and in 1934, the Uniform Drug Act enacted with the purpose of making the law uniform in various states with respect to controlling the sale and use of narcotic drugs (Abadinsky 2011).
The socialist movements of the 1960s influenced a number of government policies, including anti-drug policy. The institutions adopted a newly created strategic approach: reducing demand by rehabilitating large numbers of drug addicts. For example, in 1961 California established a civil commitment program in which drug addicts were taken into custody and committed like mentally ill people in need of hospitalization to a non-punitive period of confinement and drug treatment. Confinement was followed by a period of aftercare. The 1960s and 1970s also experienced a rise in the popularity of the therapeutic-community approach to treating addiction, the best known being Synanon in California and Daytop Village in New York.
5

Operated by recovered addicts, these drug-free centers use a variety of talking and confrontational therapies mixed with aspects of behavior modification (Abadinsky 2011).
3. Federal Legislation Since the Controlled Substances Act of 1970 The optimistic atmosphere of the 1960s did not continue too long and with the help of
alarming statistics on drug abuse, drug problem became a major political issue in 1970s. The two new approaches to dealing with drug abuse adopted by the federal government: (a) reducing availability by investigating and prosecuting traffickers and (b) reducing demand by preventing addiction and treating addicts. The Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act of 1970 authorized federal agencies to increase their efforts at prevention and rehabilitation through a program of grants to special projects. The legislation also introduced five schedules into which all controlled substances could be placed with regards to their potential for abuse; established additional reporting obligations for manufacturers, distributors, and dispensers; imposed new regulations for the importation of controlled substances; and established the Commission on Marijuana and Drug Abuse. Also in 1973 the Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) within the Department of Justice after reorganization plans (Abadinsky 2011; Newton 2010).
With the involvement of various conservative interest groups, political landscape became more delicate to the drugs in 1980s. The Congress responded those demands from anti-drug lobbies and with the Federal Reform Sentencing Act of 1984, brought new minimum mandatory sentences for convictions for various types of substance abuse. Furthermore, the law established new mandatory minimum sentences for drug offenses committed near schools, mandated prison sentences for serious drug felonies, and created probationary penalties for less serious offenses. After two years, the Congress further increased sanctions against substance abuse convictions by
6

establishing new sentences for cocaine possession. Continuing a historical trend that singles out minorities in legislation of this kind, the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 provided for a mandatory minimum sentence of 5 to 40 years for cocaine possession, a sentence that could not be suspended nor was it subject to parole. The inequity in the law was based on the fact that the mandatory minimum sentence was required for possession of 500 grams of powder cocaine (by far the drug of choice among middle- and upper-class whites), or five grams of crack cocaine (much more popular among blacks and lower-income men and women). Two years later, Congress extended this policy in the Omnibus Drug Abuse Act of 1988 by imposing a five-year mandatory sentence for possession of three grams of crack cocaine for second-time offenders and for possession of one gram of crack cocaine for third-time offenders (Newton 2010). Scholars like Chomsky (1998; 2002) saw these regulations as an instrument of population control and believe that such measures are the least effective way in tackling with the real problem. Instead, he considers that, solutions based on incarceration and punishments do not have a function other than increasing prison population with non-violent drug offenders, gets rid of superfluous population, and frighten everybody else.
Lastly, in August 2010, Congress enacted Fair Sentencing Act, which reduced the disparity between United States federal criminal penalties for crack cocaine and powder cocaine offenses from a 100:1 ratio to an 18:1 ratio, based on the number of grams of cocaine in possession and eliminated the five-year mandatory minimum sentence for simple possession of crack cocaine, among other provisions. Many scholars also saw this act as a legislation that reduces racial disparity in the fair proceeding (FAMM, 2010).
Federal policymakers has also begun to focus on other aspects of the nation’s substance abuse problem; in many cases, they have given more serious attention to other approaches to
7

solving this problem, such as the educational, prevention, and treatment approaches. The Congress and many state legislatures also recognized the potential value of educating young people about the dangers of substance abuse and began to commit tax dollars to several programs all around the country, especially the problem areas of the metroplexes (Newton 2010).
5. Conclusions Federal government and a number of states have employed a combination of methods to
tackle with the existing problem of drug abuse. Those measures included severe punitive and preventive methods, such as increased prison sentences and harsh law enforcement implications for those convicted of possessing, producing, transporting, and selling illegal drugs. In due course, harsh punitive understanding left its place to softer solutions such as educational and treatment programs for addicts. Demand reduction and supply control became the main course of action especially after 1970s. Furthermore, other social mechanisms were also came into use such as programs for youths and minorities, who were considered as high-risk groups. In conclusion, rather than a one size fits all solution, a combination of different methods became prominent in dealing with substance abuse and currently, education, prevention, and rehabilitation are the main elements of this campaign.
